//Symmetric Tree
//Given the root of a binary tree, check whether it is a mirror of itself (i.e., symmetric around its center).
//Example 1:
//Input: root = [1,2,2,3,4,4,3]
//Output: true
//Example 2:
//Input: root = [1,2,2,null,3,null,3]
//Output: false


Brute Force Approach -> (Store Mirror Traversals)
Compare the left subtree and right subtree by storing their mirror traversals in separate arrays and checking whether they match.

class Solution {
public:
    bool isSymmetric(TreeNode* root) {
        if(root == nullptr) {
            return true;
        }
        queue<TreeNode*> q;
        q.push(root);
        while(!q.empty()) {
            int size = q.size();
            vector<int> level;
            for(int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
                TreeNode* node = q.front();
                q.pop();
                if(node == nullptr) {
                    level.push_back(INT_MIN);
                    continue;
                }
                level.push_back(node->val);
                q.push(node->left);
                q.push(node->right);
            }
            int left = 0;
            int right = level.size() - 1;
            while(left < right) {
                if(level[left] != level[right]) {
                    return false;
                }
                left++;
                right--;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
};

Intuition ->
Generate a traversal for the left subtree.
Generate a mirrored traversal for the right subtree.
If both traversals are identical, the tree is symmetric.
Otherwise, it is not.

Complexity Analysis ->
Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes in the tree
Reason:
Every node is visited once.
Space Complexity -> O(n)
Reason:
Extra arrays are used to store traversals.

Optimal Approach -> (Recursive Mirror Check)
class Solution {
public:
    bool isMirror(TreeNode* left, TreeNode* right) {
        if(left == nullptr && right == nullptr) {
            return true;
        }
        if(left == nullptr || right == nullptr) {
            return false;
        }
        if(left->val != right->val) {
            return false;
        }
        return isMirror(left->left, right->right) &&
               isMirror(left->right, right->left);
    }
    bool isSymmetric(TreeNode* root) {
        return isMirror(root->left, root->right);
    }
};


Intuition ->
For a tree to be symmetric:
left->val == right->val
and
left->left  ↔  right->right
and
left->right ↔ right->left
In other words:
Left subtree must be a mirror image of the right subtree.

At every step:
Check if both nodes are null.
Check if only one node is null.
Check if values match.
Recursively compare mirror children.
Complexity Analysis ->

Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes in the tree
Reason:
Every node is visited exactly once.

Space Complexity -> O(h)
where:
h = height of the tree
Reason:
Recursive call stack stores at most h calls at one time.

Worst Case:
O(n)
for a skewed tree.

Best/Balanced Tree:
O(log n)

Dry Run of Optimal Approach

Input
        1
      /   \
     2     2
    / \   / \
   3   4 4   3

Call:
isMirror(root->left, root->right)
↓
isMirror(2,2)

Step 1
Compare:
2 ↔ 2
Values match.
Now check:
isMirror(3,3)
AND
isMirror(4,4)
Step 2

Compare:

3 ↔ 3

Values match.

Now check:

isMirror(NULL,NULL)
AND
isMirror(NULL,NULL)

Both return:

true

So:

isMirror(3,3) = true
Step 3

Compare:

4 ↔ 4

Values match.

Now check:

isMirror(NULL,NULL)
AND
isMirror(NULL,NULL)

Both return:

true

So:

isMirror(4,4) = true
Step 4

Return:

true && true

↓

true

Final Answer:

true
Dry Run of Non-Symmetric Tree

Input
        1
      /   \
     2     2
      \     \
       3     3

Call:
isMirror(2,2)
Good.
Now compare:
left->left = NULL
right->right = 3
Call:
isMirror(NULL,3)

One node is null and the other is not.
Return:
false
Final Answer:
false

